== Implications

=== For Business Strategy

The findings suggest that reputation management has evolved from a reactive communication function into a strategic, quasi-legal tactic for competitive positioning. When defamation-based takedown procedures yield removal success rates above 80%, suppression becomes a predictable input in marketing operations rather than an exceptional legal remedy. This procedural reliability allows firms to incorporate deletion services into reputation budgets, outsource compliance tasks to specialized agencies, and optimize perceived quality scores through legal rather than experiential means.

For individual businesses, the cost–benefit structure favors suppression: deletion is faster, cheaper, and more certain than rectifying service quality or generating offsetting positive feedback. However, the apparent short-term benefits of “reputation laundering” obscure longer-term risks. By depending on concealment rather than improvement, firms forgo genuine quality signals that could guide operational learning. Furthermore, the homogenization of visible ratings may erode differentiation, making competition increasingly driven by legal agility instead of consumer satisfaction. As Löschagenturen proliferate, reputation itself risks commodification — shifting from a trust-based attribute of performance into a purchasable output.

